          Additional informationPublisher’s note Springer Nature remains neutral with regard to jurisdictional claims in published maps and institutional affiliations.Extended dataExtended Data Fig. 1 Comparison between random forest model estimates and observations for topsoil (0-20 cm) CH4 emission, N2O emission, SOC density, and rice dry matter yield at the training and testing phases.a, samples in the top 20 cm soil layer in rice paddies. b-e, measurements (CH4 emission, N2O emission, SOC density, and rice yield) during 1961 to 2020 were randomly selected to train the random forest models and validate the spatiotemporal prediction ability of the models. The dashed gray line shows the 1:1 line. The red line shows the performance of the model during the training phase, and the blue one indicates that during the testing phase. The black dashed line shows the prediction accuracy of the model compared to all measurements, including training and testing samples. Model performance was evaluated using two-sided ordinary least-squares linear regression between observations and random forest estimates for the training, testing and combined datasets. The fitted slopes, R2 values and P values are shown in the panels. R2, the coefficient of determination; MAE, means absolute error; NRMSE, normalization root means square error. Map in a generated using ArcGIS v10.2 with data from Esri.Source dataExtended Data Fig. 2 Comparison of Random Forest model estimates and observations under continuous and non-continuous irrigation based on measurements of topsoil (0–20 cm) CH4 emissions, N2O emissions, SOC density, and rice dry matter yield.a, Sample distribution at irrigation experimental sites with measurements of topsoil (0–20 cm) CH4 emissions, N2O emissions, SOC density, and rice dry matter yield. b, Comparison between model estimates and observations for CH4 emissions, N2O emissions, SOC density, and rice yield from 1961 to 2020. The dashed grey line indicates the 1:1 line. Blue symbols and lines represent continuous irrigation (CI), and red symbols and lines represent non-continuous irrigation (Non-CI). c, Comparison of mean observed and simulated values under CI and Non-CI conditions. Points represent mean values and error bars indicate the uncertainty range of the corresponding experimental group. Model performance was evaluated using two-sided ordinary least-squares linear regression between observations and random forest estimates for the training, testing and combined datasets. R2, the coefficient of determination; n, the numbers of site-year data; MAE, mean absolute error; NRMSE, normalization root means square error. Other comparisons under different practices were shown in SI Appendix, Figs. S5–S10. Map in a generated using ArcGIS v10.2 with data from Esri.Source dataExtended Data Fig. 3 Decadal trajectories of global rice-paddy CH4 and N2O emissions, SOC dynamics, yield, and net soil GHG emissions across RF, DLEM, and observations.Decadal means (1960s–2010s) of global rice-paddy CH4 and N2O emissions, topsoil SOC stock (0–20 cm), SOC stock change–derived CO2-equivalent emissions or removals (negative values indicate net removals), rice yield, and net soil GHG emissions are shown for the RF model (red), DLEM (blue), observation-based synthesis or meta-analysis (green), and their mean estimate (black). CH4 and N2O are expressed as CO2-equivalents using 100-year GWPs, and the SOC-related CO2-equivalent term is derived from decadal SOC stock change using stock-change accounting. For RF and DLEM, each point represents the mean of annual values within a decade (n = 10 years). Error bars indicate the uncertainty associated with each estimate. Observation-based estimates represent decadal synthesis values compiled from available datasets for each decade.Source dataExtended Data Fig. 4 Spatial comparison of topsoil CH4 emissions, N2O emissions, SOC density, and rice dry matter yield estimated by the Random Forest model, DLEM, and meta-analysis.Maps show the global spatial patterns of (a) CH4 emissions, (b) N2O emissions, (c) SOC density (0–20 cm), and (d) rice dry matter yield. Panels (e-h) compare regional distributions across ten rice-growing regions plus the global total. The x-axis abbreviations denote GLO, global; NAM, North America; EUR, Europe; MID, Middle East; RUS, Russia; EAS, East Asia; SAM, South America; AF, Africa; SAS, South Asia; SEAS, Southeast Asia; and OCE, Oceania. In panels e-h, RF is shown as boxplots, with centre lines indicating the median, boxes indicating the interquartile range, and whiskers indicating the full range of grid-cell values within each region. DLEM values (blue markers) represent regional means across all rice-paddy grid cells, with error bars indicating the full range of grid-cell values within each region. Meta-analysis values (red markers) represent regional means across observation sites, with error bars indicating the range of site-level values within each region. Sample sizes therefore differ among regions and approaches, corresponding to the number of rice-paddy grid cells for RF and DLEM and the number of observation sites for meta-analysis within each region. Maps in a–d generated using ArcGIS v10.2 with data from Esri.Source dataExtended Data Fig. 5 Regional contributions to the global change in soil GHG components between 2001–2020 and 1961–1980.Bars show each region’s share (%) of the global net change from 1961–1980 to 2001–2020 for CH4 emissions (green, ΔCH4), N2O emissions (blue, ΔN2O), the SOC stock change–derived CO2-equivalent term (pink; ΔCO2, positive indicates net emissions and negative indicates net removals), and net soil GHG emissions (grey). Percentages are calculated as the regional net change divided by the corresponding global net change for each component. Map generated using ArcGIS v10.2 with data from Esri.Source dataExtended Data Fig. 6 Attribution of long-term changes in soil GHG components to environmental and management drivers in Africa and East Asia (1961–2020).(a) Driver contributions to changes in soil CH4 emissions in African rice paddies. (b–c) Driver contributions to changes in soil CH4 emissions and the SOC stock change–derived CO2-equivalent term in East Asian rice paddies over 1961–2020. Drivers include synthetic nitrogen fertilizer (Nfer), synthetic phosphorus fertilizer (Pfer), manure, straw return (Straw), irrigation (IRR), climate change (CLM), atmospheric CO2 fertilization effect (CO2), and nitrogen deposition (Ndep).Source dataExtended Data Fig. 7 Effects of synthetic N fertilizer (Nfer), manure (MAN), straw residue return (Res), irrigation, tillage, and biochar (Bio) on CH4 emissions, N2O emissions, SOC density, and rice yield in global rice paddies over the study period based on the RF model, DLEM, and meta-analysis.n is the number of data records. Boxplots show the distributions of observation-based values (Obs) under contrasting management conditions for each practice. Centre lines indicate the median, boxes indicate the interquartile range, and whiskers indicate the full range of values. Blue squares and green squares indicate the corresponding estimates from the RF model and DLEM, respectively. n denotes the number of observation records for each comparison. Res, residue return; No-Res, no residue return; CI, continuous irrigation; Non-CI, non-continuous irrigation; Till, conventional tillage; No-Till, no-tillage; Nfer, synthetic N fertilizer application; No-Nfer, no synthetic N fertilizer; MAN, manure application; No-MAN, no manure application; Bio, biochar application; No-Bio, no biochar application.Source dataExtended Data Fig. 8 Spatial effects (%) of residue incorporation, non-continuous irrigation, and no tillage to net soil GHG emissions, CH4 emissions, N2O emissions, and SOC stock in global rice paddies over the study period.Spatial effects (%) of residue incorporation (a–d), non-continuous irrigation (e–h) and no tillage (i–l) on net soil GHG emissions (a, e, i), CH4 emissions (b, f, j), N2O emissions (c, g, k) and SOC stock (d, h, l) in global rice paddies over the study period. The effects of other management practices, including synthetic N fertilizer, P fertilizer, manure and biochar, are shown in Supplementary Fig. S16. Maps were generated using ArcGIS v10.2 with data from Esri.Extended Data Fig. 9 Spatial changes (kg CO2eq ha−1) in net soil GHG emissions, CH4, N2O, and SOC change-derived CO2-equivalent emissions/removals induced by optimal management practices (OPT) relative to current inputs (CU) in global rice paddies under SSP2-4.5 (2031–2050).a-d, the spatial impacts of CU; e-h, the spatial impacts of OPT; i-l, the difference of the impacts between OPT and CU. Maps generated using ArcGIS v10.2 with data from Esri.Extended Data Fig. 10 Spatial distribution of major optimized management changes and their associated net soil GHG responses relative to current input levels under SSP2-4.5 (2031–2050).a, c, e, g and i show the optimal change rates (%) for straw incorporation, biochar, synthetic N fertilizer, manure and synthetic P fertilizer, respectively. b, d, f, h and j show the corresponding changes in net soil GHG emissions (kg CO2eq ha−1). Negative values indicate emission reductions relative to current inputs, and positive values indicate emission increases. Maps generated using ArcGIS v10.2 with data from Esri.Supplementary informationSupplementary Information (download PDF )Supplementary Text 1 (Methods), Figs. 1–21, Tables 1–6 and references.Reporting Summary (download PDF )Source dataSource Data Fig. 2 (download XLSX )Statistical source data.Source Data Fig. 3 (download XLSX )Statistical source data.Source Data Fig. 4 (download XLSX )Statistical source data.Source Data Fig. 5 (download XLSX )Statistical source data.Source Data Fig. 6 (download XLSX )Statistical source data.Source Data Extended Data Fig. 1 (download XLSX )Statistical source data.Source Data Extended Data Fig. 2 (download XLSX )Statistica